newsArticles.title: NASA Sets Coverage for ULA, Astrobotic Artemis Robotic Moon Launch
newsArticles.summary: On January 8, NASA, in collaboration with United Launch Alliance and Astrobotic, will launch the first commercial robotic moon mission from Cape Canaveral, culminating in a lunar landing on February 23, with live coverage available from January 4.

newsArticles.title: NASA’s Juno to Get Close Look at Jupiter’s Volcanic Moon Io on Dec. 30
newsArticles.summary: The orbiter has performed 56 flybys of Jupiter and documented close encounters with three of the gas giant’s four largest moons. NASA’s Juno spacecraft will on Saturday, Dec. 30, make the closest flyby of Jupiter’s moon Io that any spacecraft has made in over 20 years.

newsArticles.title: Ringing in the Holidays
newsArticles.summary: In a recent image from the James Webb Space Telescope, Uranus and its rings are vividly captured, showcasing the planet's polar cap and dynamic storms.

newsArticles.title: Meet the Infrared Telescopes That Paved the Way for NASA’s Webb
newsArticles.summary: The Webb telescope has opened a new window onto the universe, but it builds on missions going back 40 years, including Spitzer and the Infrared Astronomical Satellite.

newsArticles.title: NASA’s Deep Space Network Turns 60 and Prepares for the Future
newsArticles.summary: The agency’s DSN provides critical communications and navigation services to dozens of space missions, and it’s being modernized to support dozens more.

latestNews.title: Crescent Moon Over NASA’s Kennedy Space Center
latestNews.summary: On Feb. 22, 2023, the crescent moon, Jupiter, and Venus were visible over NASA's Kennedy Space Center during preparations for the SpaceX Crew-6 mission.
